  "prompt": "What is the difference between Waldo and Waldorf?",
  "response": "Waldo and Waldorf can refer to several different things depending on the context, but commonly:\n\n1. **Waldo**:\n   - Often refers to the character \"Where's Waldo?\" from the popular series of children's books in which the goal is to find the character, Waldo, in various crowded scenes. He wears a distinct red-and-white striped shirt, hat, and glasses.\n   - \"Waldo\" can also be a given name.\n\n2. **Waldorf**:\n   - Most known for Waldorf salad, which is a salad made from apples, celery, grapes, and walnuts, dressed in mayonnaise, created in the late 19th century at the Waldorf Astoria Hotel in New York City.\n   - Waldorf can refer to the Waldorf Astoria Hotel, a luxury hotel originally in New York and now part of a global chain of hotels.\n   - It can refer to the Waldorf education system, developed by Rudolf Steiner, emphasizing holistic, integrative learning.\n\nIn pop culture, Waldorf is known as one of the two elderly Muppet characters, Statler and Waldorf, who humorously critique the others from their theater box seats.\n\nRemember to consider the context in which Waldo and Waldorf are mentioned for accurate interpretation.",
